Israeli Stocks: Teva, Ratio Oil, El Al Airlines, Sunflower

-- B y   S h a r o n   W r o b e l
-- 
2011-08-15T14:14:28Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-15/israeli-stocks-ratio-oil-exploration-el-al-airlines-sunflower.html
Israel ’s TA-25 Index dropped for the
first time in three days, declining 0.7 percent to 1,091.04 at
the 4:30 p.m. close in Tel Aviv. Investors traded about 1.05
billion shekels ($299 million) of shares and convertible
securities today, according to Tel Aviv Stock Exchange data.  The following stocks rose or fell today. Symbols are in
parentheses.  El Al Israel Airlines (ELAL)  Ltd climbed 3.8 percent,
the biggest gain since March 16, to 0.802 shekel. The country’s
largest carrier signed an accord that will gradually increase
the amount it receives in government subsidies to cover security
costs.  Lapidoth-Heletz LP (LPHLL IT) rose 2.1 percent to 0.148
shekel, the highest level since Aug. 4. The Israeli government
lifted a warning that the gas and oil explorer may lose drilling
rights at its Heletz 41 site.  Ratio Oil Exploration 1992 LP (RATIL)   increased to the
highest since Aug. 4, advancing 2.9 percent to 0.388 shekel. The
oil and gas explorer and its partners at the Gal site have
applied for two drilling licenses.  Sunflower Sustainable Investments Ltd. (SNFL)   surged 5.1
percent to 9.14 shekels, the highest since May 29. The developer
of photovoltaic solar energy projects will record a pre-tax gain
of 16 million shekels in the third quarter for the sale of its
rights to two sites in Hadera, Israel.  Teva Pharmaceutical Industries Ltd. (TEVA)   plunged to
the lowest since January 2007, dropping 3 percent to 138.30
shekels. Pfizer Inc. said it won a patent infringement case
against the world’s largest generic drug maker that prevents the
company from marketing a generic version of the impotence drug,
Viagra, until 2019.  To contact the reporter on this story:
{Sharon Wrobel} in  Tel Aviv  at 
